Now I have a thorough understanding of the codebase patterns. Let me compile the comprehensive answer.

---

## TigerBeetle Patterns Relevant to FFI Extern Structs, Init Methods, `undefined`, and `@sizeOf`

### 1. `extern struct` for ABI-Stable Structures

TigerBeetle uses `extern struct` deliberately and extensively for any type that crosses an ABI boundary or is stored to disk. The pattern is consistent: every `extern struct` in the public FFI path or on-disk path is accompanied by `comptime` assertions proving its layout.

#### The canonical public API types ([`src/tigerbeetle.zig`](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/tigerbeetle.zig#L10-L32))

```zig
pub const Account = extern struct {
    id: u128,
    debits_pending: u128,
    // ...
    reserved: u32,
    ledger: u32,
    code: u16,
    flags: AccountFlags,
    timestamp: u64,

    comptime {
        assert(stdx.no_padding(Account));
        assert(@sizeOf(Account) == 128);
        assert(@alignOf(Account) == 16);
    }
};
```

Every disk-facing or FFI-facing `extern struct` has a matching `comptime {}` block that asserts three things: no implicit padding, a hard-coded size, and alignment. If the struct size ever drifts, the build fails at compile time.

#### The opaque FFI handle ([`src/clients/c/tb_client_exports.zig`](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/clients/c/tb_client_exports.zig#L11-L23))

```zig
pub const tb_client_t = extern struct {
    @"opaque": [4]u64,

    pub inline fn cast(self: *tb_client_t) *tb.ClientInterface {
        return @ptrCast(self);
    }

    comptime {
        assert(@sizeOf(tb_client_t) == @sizeOf(tb.ClientInterface));
        assert(@bitSizeOf(tb_client_t) == @bitSizeOf(tb.ClientInterface));
        assert(@alignOf(tb_client_t) == @alignOf(tb.ClientInterface));
    }
};
```

This is the exact pattern for an FFI opaque state object: a fixed-size array of `u64` hides the real internal type. The `comptime` block asserts that the opaque buffer and the real type are byte-for-byte the same size and alignment. The `cast()` method is a zero-cost `@ptrCast` to recover the real pointer.

The same relationship exists between `Packet.Extern` and the internal `Packet` type, where the external type exposes a `[64]u8 opaque` field for internal bookkeeping ([`src/clients/c/tb_client/packet.zig`](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/clients/c/tb_client/packet.zig#L136-L157)):

```zig
comptime {
    assert(@sizeOf(Extern) % @alignOf(Extern) == 0);
    assert(@alignOf(Extern) == 8);

    assert(@sizeOf(Packet) == @sizeOf(Extern));
    assert(@alignOf(Packet) == @alignOf(Extern));

    // Asserting the fields are identical.
    for (std.meta.fields(Extern)) |field_extern| {
        if (std.mem.eql(u8, field_extern.name, "opaque")) continue;
        // ...verify each field's type, alignment, and offset match...
    }
}
```

Note: `comptime` checks skip the `opaque` field explicitly—it is understood to be an intentional internal blob with no field-level invariants from the external view.

#### Pointer fields in extern unions for 32/64-bit portability ([`src/clients/c/tb_client/context.zig`](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/clients/c/tb_client/context.zig#L53-L68))

```zig
// Since the client interface is an intrusive struct allocated by the user,
// it is exported as an opaque `[_]u64` array.
// An `extern union` is used to ensure a platform-independent size for pointer fields,
// avoiding the need for different versions of `tb_client.h` on 32-bit targets.

context: extern union {
    ptr: ?*anyopaque,
    int_ptr: u64,
},
vtable: extern union {
    ptr: *const VTable,
    int_ptr: u64,
},
```

Pointer-sized fields inside an `extern struct` exposed over FFI are wrapped in an `extern union` with a `u64` alternative. This forces the field to always be 8 bytes wide regardless of the target pointer size, eliminating `tb_client.h` from needing 32-bit vs 64-bit variants.

#### `ClientInterface` has a hard size assertion ([`src/clients/c/tb_client/context.zig`](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/clients/c/tb_client/context.zig#L132-L135))

```zig
comptime {
    assert(@sizeOf(ClientInterface) == 32);
    assert(@alignOf(ClientInterface) == 8);
}
```

---

### 2. Init Methods Taking `self *` Pointers

TigerBeetle uses a **two-phase init idiom** pervasively. The struct is declared as a `var` in the caller and its address is passed to `init()`. Init does not return a new value—it writes into the existing memory via `self.*`. This is the only idiom in the codebase; there are no factory functions returning by value for non-trivial types.

#### The canonical form ([`src/lsm/node_pool.zig`](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/lsm/node_pool.zig#L30-L43))

```zig
pub fn init(pool: *NodePool, allocator: mem.Allocator, node_count: u32) !void {
    assert(node_count > 0);

    pool.* = .{
        .buffer = undefined,
        .free = undefined,
    };
    const size = node_size * node_count;
    pool.buffer = try allocator.alignedAlloc(u8, node_alignment, size);
    errdefer allocator.free(pool.buffer);

    pool.free = try std.bit_set.DynamicBitSetUnmanaged.initFull(allocator, node_count);
    errdefer pool.free.deinit(allocator);
}
```

The pattern is:
1. Immediately write a partial struct literal to `pool.*`, with fields that need allocation set to `undefined`.
2. Perform each fallible allocation in order.
3. Attach `errdefer` _after_ each allocation to roll it back in reverse order on failure.

The same pattern appears in [`src/lsm/tree.zig`](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/lsm/tree.zig#L121-L150), [`src/lsm/scan_buffer.zig`](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/lsm/scan_buffer.zig#L21-L37), and every other non-trivial init in the codebase.

#### Callers always use an `undefined` local, then call init ([`src/lsm/node_pool.zig`](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/lsm/node_pool.zig#L240-L244))

```zig
var context: TestContext = undefined;
try context.init(&prng, i);
defer context.deinit();
```

This is the standard call site pattern: declare `undefined`, then `init`, then `defer deinit`.

---

### 3. `undefined` for Internal Buffers and Arrays

TigerBeetle is deliberate about _when_ it uses `undefined` and _why_. Two distinct uses appear in the codebase.

#### Use 1: Deferred initialization in init — `undefined` as a placeholder for fields about to be filled

From [`src/lsm/scan_buffer.zig`](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/lsm/scan_buffer.zig#L43-L58):

```zig
pub fn init(
    self: *ScanBuffer,
    allocator: Allocator,
    options: struct { index: u8 },
) !void {
    self.* = .{
        .index = options.index,
        .levels = undefined,          // <-- array of LevelBuffer, each needs alloc
    };
    for (&self.levels, 0..) |*level, i| {
        errdefer for (self.levels[0..i]) |*level_| level_.deinit(allocator);
        try level.init(allocator);
    }
}
```

The `levels` array is `undefined` at struct-literal time because each element requires a separate allocation inside the subsequent loop. The key insight is that only elements [0..i) have valid state at any moment; the rest are intentionally undefined until `level.init` fills them in. This precisely matches your use-case.

#### Use 2: Avoiding large binary bloat from static initializers

From [`src/aof.zig`](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/aof.zig#L101-L113) — there is an explicit comment documenting the motivation:

```zig
// Using self.* = .{ .message = undefined } notation causes a `constants.message_size_max`
// increase in binary size, since Zig embeds the entire static initialization payload in the
// binary.
self.* = undefined;
self.magic_number = magic_number;
stdx.copy_disjoint(
    .exact,
    u8,
    self.message[0..message.header.size],
    message.buffer[0..message.header.size],
);
@memset(self.message[message.header.size..self.message.len], 0);
```

Here, `self.* = undefined` is preferred over `self.* = .{ .message = undefined }` precisely to avoid the compiler embedding a multi-megabyte zero payload in the binary. Fields are then explicitly set individually.

#### Use 3: Released/freed state — poison released items

From [`src/stdx/iops.zig`](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/stdx/iops.zig#L21-L26):

```zig
pub fn release(self: *IOPS, item: *T) void {
    item.* = undefined;   // <-- poison the released slot
    const i = self.index(item);
    assert(self.busy.is_set(i));
    self.busy.unset(i);
}
```

When a slot is returned to the pool, it is immediately set to `undefined`. This makes use-after-release in Debug mode a trap rather than silent corruption. Similarly, `deinit` functions typically end with `self.* = undefined`.

#### The IOPS array itself is `= undefined` at struct definition ([`src/stdx/iops.zig`](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/stdx/iops.zig#L12-L13))

```zig
items: [size]T = undefined,
busy: Map = .{},
```

`items` is initialized to `undefined` as a field default because all slots start unoccupied, tracked by the `busy` bitset. Only slots where `busy.is_set(i)` are valid; accessing any other is UB by design. The `busy` bitset is initialized to all-clear (`.{}`), correctly reflecting that no item is valid. This is exactly the pattern for a fixed-size array where only a tracked subset of slots has defined content.

---

### 4. `@sizeOf` and Exported Size Functions for FFI

TigerBeetle does not export a `get_size()` C function. Instead, it relies on three mechanisms:

#### Mechanism 1: Hard `@sizeOf` assertions inside `comptime {}` blocks

This is the primary pattern. Every type that crosses ABI has its size asserted at compile time:

| File | Type | Assertion |
|---|---|---|
| [`src/tigerbeetle.zig`](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/tigerbeetle.zig#L28-L32) | `Account` | `@sizeOf(Account) == 128` |
| [`src/tigerbeetle.zig`](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/tigerbeetle.zig#L112-L115) | `Transfer` | `@sizeOf(Transfer) == 128` |
| [`src/clients/c/tb_client/context.zig`](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/clients/c/tb_client/context.zig#L132-L135) | `ClientInterface` | `@sizeOf(ClientInterface) == 32` |
| [`src/clients/c/tb_client_exports.zig`](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/clients/c/tb_client_exports.zig#L18-L22) | `tb_client_t` | `@sizeOf(tb_client_t) == @sizeOf(tb.ClientInterface)` |
| [`src/clients/c/tb_client/context.zig`](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/clients/c/tb_client/context.zig#L180-L187) | `UserData` | `@sizeOf(UserData) == @sizeOf(u128)` |

#### Mechanism 2: The `tb_client_header_test.zig` cross-language round-trip test

Rather than a `get_size()` export, TigerBeetle uses a compile-time test that re-imports the generated `tb_client.h` via `@cImport` and compares every struct's Zig and C sizes field-by-field:

From [`src/clients/c/tb_client_header_test.zig`](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/clients/c/tb_client_header_test.zig#L81-L110):

```zig
.@"extern" => {
    // Ensure structs are effectively the same.
    assert(@sizeOf(ty) == @sizeOf(c_type));
    assert(@alignOf(ty) == @alignOf(c_type));

    for (std.meta.fields(ty)) |field| {
        // Check each field's offset and type against C
        const c_field_type = @TypeOf(@field(@as(c_type, undefined), field.name));
        // ...
    }
},
```

This is how TigerBeetle ensures FFI sizes are correct: not by exposing a size getter at runtime, but by asserting equivalence at compile time between the Zig and C representations.

#### Mechanism 3: `stdx.no_padding` as a necessary precondition

The [`stdx.no_padding`](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/stdx/stdx.zig#L433-L483) function is a compile-time checker that walks all fields of an `extern struct` and verifies there are no gaps:

```zig
pub fn no_padding(comptime T: type) bool {
    comptime switch (@typeInfo(T)) {
        .@"struct" => |info| {
            switch (info.layout) {
                .auto => return false,   // auto layout can never be "no padding" for FFI
                .@"extern" => {
                    var offset = 0;
                    for (info.fields) |field| {
                        const field_offset = @offsetOf(T, field.name);
                        if (offset != field_offset) return false;
                        offset += @sizeOf(field.type);
                    }
                    return offset == @sizeOf(T);
                },
                .@"packed" => return @bitSizeOf(T) == 8 * @sizeOf(T),
            }
        },
        // ...
    };
}
```

**Auto layout structs explicitly return `false`** — `no_padding` is designed to reject non-`extern`, non-`packed` structs, encoding the convention that FFI types must always be `extern`.

---

### Summary of Design Tendencies

| Pattern | TigerBeetle Behavior |
|---|---|
| FFI opaque state | Fixed `[N]u64` array `extern struct`; internal type is `@ptrCast`-ed back with `cast()` |
| Size validation | `comptime { assert(@sizeOf(T) == N); assert(@alignOf(T) == A); }` inside the type body |
| No-padding validation | `assert(stdx.no_padding(T))` always paired with size assertion on every disk/FFI type |
| Init taking `self *` | `self.* = .{ .field_needing_alloc = undefined, ... }` then fallible sub-inits with `errdefer` |
| `undefined` for unoccupied slots | Field default `= undefined` plus a sideband bitset tracking which slots are valid |
| `undefined` to avoid binary bloat | `self.* = undefined` followed by explicit field assignment when large arrays are involved |
| Released slots | `item.* = undefined` in `release()` to poison use-after-free in Debug |
| No exported size C function | C header is auto-generated and cross-validated against Zig via `@cImport` + `comptime` asserts |
| Pointer fields in extern structs | Wrapped in `extern union { ptr: *T, int_ptr: u64 }` for 32/64-bit portability |
